[2] Cambodia
Date: Tue 19 Jul 2016
Source: The Phnom Penh Post [edited]
http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/measles-confirmation-prompts-fears-action


A total of 2 measles cases investigated by the government in recent weeks have been confirmed positive, bringing the total number to 5 this year [2016] and causing concern among health officials about a possible outbreak after the World Health Organization declared the country measles-free just last year [2015].

The latest cases - found in an 8-month-old in Phnom Penh and a 10-month-old in Svay Rieng province - have the same strain that caused a deadly outbreak in Vietnam in 2014, Ork Vichit, manager of Cambodia's National Immunization Program, said yesterday. He said the transmission might have migrated from a neighboring country. "It's an issue that we have to solve," he said. "We still have some intervention in the areas where the cases were identified. People are being provided vaccines."

The immunization program has requested USD 200 000 for operational costs to cover the intervention efforts, Vichit said. It has also requested 200 000 measles vaccines from the Measles and Rubella Initiative, a global organization, to conduct a follow-up intervention effort to vaccinate people in the areas where the 3 prior cases were identified earlier this year [2016], he added.

In May, a case was identified in Takeo province's Bati district, where another case had cropped up in January, he said. The 1st case was identified in Kampong Speu's Kong Pisei district in January.

A WHO Cambodia expert was not available for comment.

[Byline: Yesenia Amaro]

